HMMs: generation and inference

Toy example 2

Generate data with the hidden state transitions (same as before) \[ {\mathbf{A}}= \begin{pmatrix} 0.9 & 0 & 0.1 \\ 0.1 & 0.9 & 0 \\ 0 & 0.1 & 0.9 \end{pmatrix} \] and the emission probabilities \[ {\mathbf{B}}= \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0.1 & 0.35 & 0.55 \\ 0 & 0.1 & 0.45 & 0.45 \\ 0.6 & 0.3 & 0.1 & 0 \end{pmatrix} \] A sequence of \(x\) and \(y\) of length \(n=500\).

pi = c(1/3, 1/3, 1/3)
A = rbind(c(0.9, 0, 0.1), c(0.1, 0.9, 0), c(0, 0.1, 0.9))
B = rbind(c(0, 0.1, 0.45-0.1, 0.45+0.1), c(0, 0.1, 0.45, 0.45), c(0.6, 0.3, 0.1, 0))

n = 500
hmm_obs = generate_discrete_HMM(n, pi, A, B)
df_true = data.frame(t = 1:n, x = hmm_obs$x)
ggplot(df_true, aes(t, x, group=1)) + 
  geom_path() + geom_point(aes(col = x)) + 
  theme_bw() + xlab("") + ggtitle("True hidden sequence")

Inference

res = gibbs_sampling_hmm(y = hmm_obs$y, n_hidden_states = nrow(A), alpha0 = 0.1, max_iter = 1500, burnin = 500)

# relabel the latent states to obtain best match to the true B matrix
res_relabelled = match_states(res$trace_x, res$trace_A, res$trace_B, true_x = hmm_obs$x, k = nrow(A))

Visualise samples of \(x_{1:T}\)

Each draw from the posterior is shown as a grey line. The true states are shown as coloured points.

Traceplots of the elements in \({\mathbf{A}}\)

Panel \((i, j)\) shows the traceplot for the element \({\mathbf{A}}_{ij}\). The red dotted line shows the true value.

Traceplots of the elements in \({\mathbf{B}}\)

Panel \((i, j)\) shows the traceplot for the element \({\mathbf{B}}_{ij}\). The red dotted line shows the true value.
